We first calculate the Free Cash Flow (FCF) and then determine the Current Assets Turnover Ratio.

Step 1. Free Cash Flow (FCF)

The example calculation shows that FCF is determined by taking the Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities and subtracting the capital expenditures (which here are those cash flows from investing activities such as the purchase of fixed assets). In our statement:

• Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –4,900,875.61  
• Purchase of Fixed Assets (cash flow from investing activities) = –1,593,203.67

Thus, FCF = Operating Cash Flow + Cash Flow from Investing Activities  
     = –4,900,875.61 + (–1,593,203.67)  
     = –6,494,079.28

Step 2. Current Assets Turnover Ratio

This ratio is calculated as the Main Business Revenue divided by the End Current Assets at the period end. In our data:

• Main Business Revenue = 8,361,807.77  
• Total Current Assets (End_amount) = 8,538,597.02

Thus, Current Assets Turnover Ratio = 8,361,807.77 / 8,538,597.02  
    ≈ 0.979 (approximately 0.98 when rounded to two decimal places)

Our final answer in the required format is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Free Cash Flow (FCF)": "-6494079.28",
    "Current Assets Turnover Ratio": "0.98"
  }
}
